title: For Sale:  VEPR 7.62x54r 20.5" + POSP + ammo & extras
postcontent:
Made in the Molot factory in Russia where the best quality AK derived guns come from is the 20.5" VEPR.  A batch was imported through Robinson Arms several years back and we've just had a run of them over the last year or so and they're about gone.  Molot will only be doing 23" 7.62x54r VEPRs with an unfinished stock and normal front sight post and there are only a few batches coming, one in July, maybe one towards the end of the year according to Wolf.  Immediately after this model dried up, their value has soared.  

The VEPR follows the RPK design with thick barrels, 1.5mm thick receivers, and reinforced receivers and trunions.  There is nothing better than these, not the saigas, not the bulgarians, and definitely nothing American made.  

Chambered in 7.62x54r (about on par with 30-06) in the 20.5" thick barrel with integrated sights on the gas block - aka "version 2" this gun can easily head out to 1000 yards and more.  I've removed the light layer of lacquer it came with and applied 4 coats of tung oil on the walnut stock and handguard, put a swivel stud in the handguard closer to the receiver and mounted a bipod on it - this is done to reduce barrel harmonic interruption and movement when loading the bipod.  

This gun also has the best Russian glass you can get, the POSP 8x42B PRO scope made in Belarus.  This scope is the best they got in the Motherland and it is current military issue.  It has the larger dials for greater reticle/range/wind management.  It's not even listed yet at Kalinka.  The glass on this is on par with the higher quality German optics.  This scope also has a low-light red lit reticle.   I also have a Krebs Custom safety lever which is designed to be manipulated with the fire control hand/finger, it also has a bolt hold open slot to keep the bolt carrier back.

The bipod is a simple Blackhawk sporter that does the job.  I've also installed a CNC Warrior muzzle device that greatly redirects gas to reduce felt recoil some and keep the nose down, it also tames the fireballs you get from surplus 54r ammo.  I didn't have the heart to replace the beautiful walnut stocks so I haven't bubba'd it with polymer furniture though I am tempted.

I'm including 880 rounds in 2 sealed tins of 148grain silver tipped Bulgarian (10/72) ammo.  THis was $200 plus for me to buy.

The gun cost me 1300, optic 325, bipod 40, tins of ammo are 100 each, muzzle device 25.  This gun has maybe 50 flawless rounds through it with DMR (designated marksman rifle) precision of just under 3" at 100m.   I can hit the 200 and 300 yard plates at the range readily with this gun and I'm sure i could do 3MOA quality hits out to 1000 as this cartridge can do it.  With quality 7N1 ammo or American made 54r ammo, this will likely be a 2MOA gun or better.

I'm asking $1700 for all of it which is a loss to me and definitely of no profit to me.  The optic comes with a camoflage padded bag (from Belarus), there's 2 Russian 5 round mags with it, and a handsome box it all came in.  I'm not desperate to sell so I'm not very flexible on the price.  I will require a bill of sale and verify that you are a Montana citizen.  The only real trade I'd entertain would be for a S&W 1911sc or a STI Trojan 5 and cash.

YOU GET:
-Molot VEPR 20.5" in 7.62x54r with two included 5rd mags (10 rd mags available at  Carolina Shooter's Supply), cleaning kit that comes with the gun included
-POSP 8x42B PRO scope with low-light red illumination (switch) with camo bag
-Bipod installed
-CNC Warrior Russian muzzle device 
-Two 440 round sealed tins of Bulgarian silver tip ammo (and a can opener!)

title: For Sale:  Colt SAA 1873  Peacemaker-- Serial  Number 40??
postcontent:
I have what could possibly be an 1873 production Colt Single Action Army revolver!  This could be the 40th SAA pistol made.
A family member purchased this pistol more than 20 years ago as a cowboy action pistol. I have inherited this revolver and have done a considerable amount of research. A local expert was of the opinion that this was the original 40th SAA produced but some parts had been changed and modified over the last 140 years. I have looked at online pictures and cannot find the exact pistol combination.  The serial number 40 is stamped on the underside of the frame,  two places under the grips, and on the feed side of the cylinder.  The grips are wood,  each with a Colt medallion.
The barrel is 4.75" which should have been an original 7.5". 
The cylinder rotates properly but does not lock up therefore I do not recommend firing!
I have checked some online forums and some have suggested that it could be a "Mexican" production.  Apparently the Europeans produced these in the late 1800's  and imported then through Mexico.
I cannot verify any of this with any certainty.  It is one of two situations: a Mexican produced gun or the original 40th produced frame with changed parts.
 If it is the real deal the pistol is almost priceless.  If it isn't,  similar Mexican models sell for well over $1000 in this condition.
Gun is antique and sold as-is.
My need for quick cash could make you a fortune.  Otherwise this is a more than fair price for a relic!

title: For Sale:  Winchester 12ga. Shotgun Model 1911 SL
postcontent:
My Winchester 12ga Model 1911 SL was made in 1912.(NEEDS REPAIR WORK) The following is some of the history of this shotgun.
The Winchester 1911 SL holds five shells in a tubular magazine located under the barrel.  Around the magazine there is a coiled spring that brings the barrel back into place after the gun is fired. This is all very similar to the Browning Auto-5, but this is about where the similarities end.

The biggest difference is how the 1911 SL is loaded.  One of the parts John Browning patented was the charging tab on the bolt of the Auto-5.  That is a pretty important part of the shotgun and Winchester couldnât use one. To charge the 1911 SL the shooter had to cycle the shotgun the same way it worked when fired â by compressing the barrel to work the action.

This is not easy to do.  Winchester put a checkered area on the barrel to act as a grip.  The shooter grabbed the barrel, placed the butt of the shotgun on something hard and pulled.  Depending on how it was gripped, this could cause the muzzle to be in an unsafe place.  This is how she earned the nickname âthe widow maker.â
